00:01:59.020 --> 00:02:01.720
The big conclusion
after four years of work

00:02:01.720 --> 00:02:05.140
has been to ask questions
about how can design in tech

00:02:05.140 --> 00:02:06.670
be more inclusive.

00:02:06.670 --> 00:02:08.630
If we can figure
this out, we can

00:02:08.630 --> 00:02:13.990
unlock incredible possibility
and profitability.

00:02:13.990 --> 00:02:15.370
The problem with
the word design,

00:02:15.370 --> 00:02:18.520
however, is that it
means too many things.

00:02:18.520 --> 00:02:22.450
So the report defines design
as three kinds of design.

00:02:22.450 --> 00:02:25.690
There's classical design,
like your glasses.

00:02:25.690 --> 00:02:29.380
There's design thinking-- this
idea of using Post-it notes

00:02:29.380 --> 00:02:31.930
to create structure of ideas.

00:02:31.930 --> 00:02:33.970
And there's
computational design--

00:02:33.970 --> 00:02:37.170
the kind of design that
is powered by Moore's law.

00:02:37.170 --> 00:02:38.890
It's a different kind of design.

00:02:38.890 --> 00:02:43.220
It uses a material that
didn't exist 100 years ago.

00:02:43.220 --> 00:02:44.770
What's a computational designer?

00:02:44.770 --> 00:02:47.860
I've defined this as
roughly four type of things

00:02:47.860 --> 00:02:50.440
you have to have as a
computational designer.

00:02:50.440 --> 00:02:52.390
You don't have to
know how to program,

00:02:52.390 --> 00:02:54.790
but you have to be
technically literate.

00:02:54.790 --> 00:02:57.670
You also have to think
critically about technology.

00:02:57.670 --> 00:03:00.230
For you, technology
is a responsibility.

00:03:00.230 --> 00:03:02.860
So you wonder how
things are being used.

00:03:02.860 --> 00:03:04.930
You also use all
kinds of design.

00:03:04.930 --> 00:03:07.480
You aren't stuck in just
computational design.

00:03:07.480 --> 00:03:10.570
And lastly, you're very
curious about new things,

00:03:10.570 --> 00:03:14.290
because designers loved
to learn new people,

00:03:14.290 --> 00:03:18.340
new customs, new anything
because it's how they learn.

00:03:18.340 --> 00:03:22.210
So designers aren't
inherently diversity positive.

00:03:22.210 --> 00:03:24.410
It's a very important point.

00:03:24.410 --> 00:03:27.000
Now, if you think about
the value of design,

00:03:27.000 --> 00:03:29.785
it's been demonstrated
by all the M&amp;A activity--

00:03:29.785 --> 00:03:32.070
the Mergers and
Acquisition activity--

00:03:32.070 --> 00:03:32.950
of agencies.

00:03:32.950 --> 00:03:36.960
So I reported on this
report, over 20 agencies

00:03:36.960 --> 00:03:40.260
were acquired by
consulting companies,

00:03:40.260 --> 00:03:44.190
because consulting companies
are finding value in design

00:03:44.190 --> 00:03:46.290
for their clients,
which is a big deal.

00:03:46.290 --> 00:03:48.960
It never happened before.

00:03:48.960 --> 00:03:52.680
Now, the problem, however,
is that classical designers

00:03:52.680 --> 00:03:55.870
tend to dis design thinking.

00:03:55.870 --> 00:03:57.510
You know what I'm talking about?

00:03:57.510 --> 00:04:00.310
Like oh, design thinkers,
they have the Post-it notes

00:04:00.310 --> 00:04:03.100
and the Sharpie markers
with the white board.

00:04:03.100 --> 00:04:06.040
You know, classical
designers don't think of them

00:04:06.040 --> 00:04:07.810
as real designers.

00:04:07.810 --> 00:04:10.060
But I always tell
classical designers, well,

00:04:10.060 --> 00:04:12.280
they make more
money than you do.

00:04:12.280 --> 00:04:15.200
So important to note, design
thinking is not a bad thing.

00:04:15.200 --> 00:04:17.589
It's a different kind of design.

00:04:17.589 --> 00:04:20.920
Also, I found that, being in
the Silicon Valley for a while,

00:04:20.920 --> 00:04:23.210
we tend to forget there's
the rest of the world.

00:04:23.210 --> 00:04:26.440
So I'm a big fan of China
and all of the design

00:04:26.440 --> 00:04:28.060
work being done there--

00:04:28.060 --> 00:04:32.110
design of cars, design of
experiences, especially mobile,

00:04:32.110 --> 00:04:37.850
and, more recently, using AI
to design banners, designs.

00:04:37.850 --> 00:04:40.600
They're just so further
ahead that many people

00:04:40.600 --> 00:04:43.810
seem to have the impression
in the United States.

00:04:43.810 --> 00:04:48.130
And that's kind of an
embarrassing problem.

00:04:48.130 --> 00:04:49.930
Also, the other problem
I've seen in tech

00:04:49.930 --> 00:04:53.590
is that it indexes to
younger people, which

00:04:53.590 --> 00:04:55.120
is a great opportunity.

00:04:55.120 --> 00:04:58.060
But there's also an incredible
opportunity in the older

00:04:58.060 --> 00:05:01.730
generation because, I don't
know if you all know this,

00:05:01.730 --> 00:05:04.528
but you all will get older.

00:05:04.528 --> 00:05:05.840
Yeah, it's not a problem.

00:05:05.840 --> 00:05:07.230
It's a real thing.

00:05:07.230 --> 00:05:10.030
And as you get
older, things change.

00:05:10.030 --> 00:05:12.190
The first thing that
changes is your eyesight.

00:05:12.190 --> 00:05:15.130
So for all designers
who love 6.5 point,

00:05:15.130 --> 00:05:17.350
you better give it up.

00:05:17.350 --> 00:05:20.010
Looks awesome,
especially in light,

00:05:20.010 --> 00:05:23.440
but you won't be able to see
it once you hit 40-something.

00:05:23.440 --> 00:05:26.720
And at Automattic we call
this the bolder generation.

00:05:26.720 --> 00:05:27.220
Get it?

00:05:27.220 --> 00:05:28.347
Boulder?

00:05:28.347 --> 00:05:28.930
We liked that.

00:05:31.780 --> 00:05:34.360
Good news is that design
is being used sooner

00:05:34.360 --> 00:05:35.490
in the process.

00:05:35.490 --> 00:05:39.450
It used to be in tech that
you'd make the technology,

00:05:39.450 --> 00:05:41.780
and oh, my gosh,
it finally works.

00:05:41.780 --> 00:05:46.910
And you'd spray design
on called make it pretty.

00:05:46.910 --> 00:05:50.060
That was great 10 years ago,
but because the competition

00:05:50.060 --> 00:05:54.480
is so fierce now, you have to
bake design into the product.

00:05:54.480 --> 00:05:58.880
And you can see globally-- we
did a survey of 2,000 people--

00:05:58.880 --> 00:06:00.710
the trend is design
is being used

00:06:00.710 --> 00:06:03.930
earlier in the process,
which is a big deal.

00:06:03.930 --> 00:06:05.940
Now, when we talk about
computational design,

00:06:05.940 --> 00:06:10.370
however, it's important to note
that computational design uses

00:06:10.370 --> 00:06:12.040
the computer.

00:06:12.040 --> 00:06:14.550
And if you were-- who
was there in the '80s?

00:06:14.550 --> 00:06:17.040
'80s, '80s, come on.
'80s people, right?

00:06:17.040 --> 00:06:19.980
People didn't like people who
