00:09:25.100 --> 00:09:26.670
are learning so quickly.

00:09:26.670 --> 00:09:30.320
And when they learn so
quickly, they learn bad things.

00:09:30.320 --> 00:09:33.140
I'm not sure if you remember
it, but in July 2015,

00:09:33.140 --> 00:09:37.070
the Wall Street
Journal reported how

00:09:37.070 --> 00:09:40.590
images mistakenly tagged
black people as gorillas

00:09:40.590 --> 00:09:42.380
was happening in 2015.

00:09:42.380 --> 00:09:43.730
The algorithm was fixed.

00:09:43.730 --> 00:09:44.450
Why did it exist?

00:09:44.450 --> 00:09:49.310
Because the database had more
light faces than darker faces,

00:09:49.310 --> 00:09:51.920
so the database was dumb.

00:09:51.920 --> 00:09:56.390
And so these data dumbness is
occurring all over the place

00:09:56.390 --> 00:09:59.180
as machine intelligence
ingests more data which

00:09:59.180 --> 00:10:02.720
contains incredible
biases that we have,

00:10:02.720 --> 00:10:06.320
unfortunately, let sit
out there for too long.

00:10:06.320 --> 00:10:08.060
So how do we change that?

00:10:08.060 --> 00:10:11.310
I think we change that by
rethinking a few things.

00:10:11.310 --> 00:10:15.080
And that is where does
technology evolve the quickest?

00:10:15.080 --> 00:10:17.870
And in the report, we pointed
out that there's two regions.

00:10:17.870 --> 00:10:20.150
Do you see the red
regions-- the hot regions?

00:10:20.150 --> 00:10:22.460
That's where all this
stuff is happening--

00:10:22.460 --> 00:10:23.930
this region of the country--

00:10:23.930 --> 00:10:25.730
New York.

00:10:25.730 --> 00:10:29.210
But if you flip the map,
this is a map of inequality--

00:10:29.210 --> 00:10:30.530
income inequality.

00:10:30.530 --> 00:10:32.760
If you flip it, you
see the exact opposite.

00:10:32.760 --> 00:10:35.090
That where tech is
not impacting is

00:10:35.090 --> 00:10:37.850
where poverty is growing the
quickest, because the skills

00:10:37.850 --> 00:10:40.970
gap is so large.

00:10:40.970 --> 00:10:43.940
This audience here is
probably in the 0.01%

00:10:43.940 --> 00:10:46.290
of the most advanced
people in the world.

00:10:46.290 --> 00:10:49.760
That said, the entire world
is behind in computation,

00:10:49.760 --> 00:10:52.690
understanding the
impact of Moore's law.

00:10:52.690 --> 00:10:56.270
And this is a very subtle
intellectual privilege problem

00:10:56.270 --> 00:10:57.870
today.

00:10:57.870 --> 00:11:01.040
So when we look at what
technology has done,

00:11:01.040 --> 00:11:04.370
it's been able to be
extremely smart at optimizing

00:11:04.370 --> 00:11:06.740
our experience, and
therefore making nothing

00:11:06.740 --> 00:11:09.850
we understand real or not real.

00:11:09.850 --> 00:11:12.260
And that we all know it's
happening, and it's amazing,

00:11:12.260 --> 00:11:14.060
but it's also quite disturbing.

00:11:14.060 --> 00:11:16.150
My mother-- by the way--
her favorite newspaper

00:11:16.150 --> 00:11:18.170
is the "National
Enquirer," so I'm always

00:11:18.170 --> 00:11:20.570
checking out the headlines.

00:11:20.570 --> 00:11:22.520
I just picked this up.

00:11:22.520 --> 00:11:23.510
Look out, Google.

00:11:23.510 --> 00:11:25.800
They know too.

00:11:25.800 --> 00:11:27.690
So is the digital
divide related somehow

00:11:27.690 --> 00:11:29.130
to poverty and inequality?

00:11:29.130 --> 00:11:32.790
I think it's hard to say
they're related or it's causal

00:11:32.790 --> 00:11:35.280
or correlated, but there's
something connected that we

00:11:35.280 --> 00:11:36.900
cannot miss.

00:11:36.900 --> 00:11:40.320
And that is that if you don't
have access to computation,

00:11:40.320 --> 00:11:42.160
you are excluded.

00:11:42.160 --> 00:11:45.730
And if you don't understand
what it can do, you're excluded.

00:11:45.730 --> 00:11:50.540
And so technology keeps
shooting off without them, us.

00:11:50.540 --> 00:11:52.190
So what's a solution?

