So remote work is neat
because it takes you out

00:12:05.150 --> 00:12:07.880
of these bubbles of tech.

00:12:07.880 --> 00:12:10.760
I guess I'm hopeful
that's at Automattic

00:12:10.760 --> 00:12:13.100
we're trying figure out
a world where WordPress

00:12:13.100 --> 00:12:14.600
is good design for all.

00:12:14.600 --> 00:12:15.750
How do we do that?

00:12:15.750 --> 00:12:18.140
We have to use the fact
that we can go anywhere

00:12:18.140 --> 00:12:19.910
because we're remote.

00:12:19.910 --> 00:12:22.690
So for instance, let's see--

00:12:22.690 --> 00:12:25.240
someone, I was
visiting Appalachia.

00:12:25.240 --> 00:12:27.170
And in Appalachia
I heard the story

00:12:27.170 --> 00:12:31.520
about how it was a coal
miner who's teaching code

00:12:31.520 --> 00:12:33.310
to ex-coal miners.

00:12:33.310 --> 00:12:35.420
And he said, you
know, you people

00:12:35.420 --> 00:12:37.600
are from the
three-dimensional world.

00:12:37.600 --> 00:12:38.510
You're 3D.

00:12:38.510 --> 00:12:41.570
You live in cities
with skyscrapers.

00:12:41.570 --> 00:12:44.600
And if you're from a smaller
city, you're in a town,

00:12:44.600 --> 00:12:46.160
you live in 2D.

00:12:46.160 --> 00:12:49.670
In 2D, you have no
skyscrapers, just streets.

00:12:49.670 --> 00:12:52.980
And he said, here in
Appalachia, we live in 1D.

00:12:52.980 --> 00:12:56.090
There's one street, and
we all live off of it.

00:12:56.090 --> 00:12:58.520
That's when I realized the
neat thing about remote work

00:12:58.520 --> 00:13:00.790
is you're zero-dimensional.

00:13:00.790 --> 00:13:04.640
And by being zero-dimensional,
you can travel anywhere.

00:13:04.640 --> 00:13:07.550
And so we're trying
to use this advantage

00:13:07.550 --> 00:13:10.760
to go into all kinds of
places, anywhere in the world,

00:13:10.760 --> 00:13:12.260
and to connect with people.

00:13:12.260 --> 00:13:15.290
And I can tell you that this
experience of being remote

00:13:15.290 --> 00:13:18.410
is a very powerful way
to reduce exclusion,

00:13:18.410 --> 00:13:21.650
because you can be including
by just going anywhere

00:13:21.650 --> 00:13:24.050
you think is necessary.

00:13:24.050 --> 00:13:27.490
Now, this is my favorite quote
by the lawyer Verna Myers.

00:13:27.490 --> 00:13:30.110
"Diversity is being
invited to the party.

00:13:30.110 --> 00:13:33.380
Inclusion is being
asked to dance."

00:13:33.380 --> 00:13:34.680
Say this over to yourself.

00:13:34.680 --> 00:13:38.960
It's such a powerful idea,
because if you don't have both,

00:13:38.960 --> 00:13:40.740
nothing occurs.

00:13:40.740 --> 00:13:43.040
And so when you ask how
to be more inclusive,

00:13:43.040 --> 00:13:44.240
it's quite easy.

00:13:44.240 --> 00:13:46.590
Just ask where do
you spend your time?

00:13:46.590 --> 00:13:48.050
Who do you hang out with?

00:13:48.050 --> 00:13:50.090
Look at the people in
the room around you?

00:13:50.090 --> 00:13:51.641
Are they diverse in some way?

00:13:51.641 --> 00:13:53.390
If they're not, you're
going to have to do

00:13:53.390 --> 00:13:55.490
something terrible to yourself.

00:13:55.490 --> 00:13:58.840
You're going to have to
make yourself uncomfortable.

00:13:58.840 --> 00:14:01.000
And it's exciting
to be uncomfortable.

00:14:01.000 --> 00:14:04.330
Oh, my gosh, you say
the dumbest things.

00:14:04.330 --> 00:14:07.780
And you stumble, and
you become stupid,

00:14:07.780 --> 00:14:10.360
and you become smarter and
a better person through it,

00:14:10.360 --> 00:14:11.110
I believe.

00:14:11.110 --> 00:14:15.670
So all of you who are not found
yourself in this way, enjoy it.

00:14:15.670 --> 00:14:18.460
It's so exciting.

00:14:18.460 --> 00:14:20.920
I'm a big entertainment
fan, and I've

00:14:20.920 --> 00:14:22.840
been tracking all
the movies that

00:14:22.840 --> 00:14:25.990
have put diversity inclusion
at the center of them.

00:14:25.990 --> 00:14:28.210
And they're doing
very well financially.

00:14:28.210 --> 00:14:31.150
Movies like "Wonder Woman,"
directed by Patty Jenkins,

00:14:31.150 --> 00:14:34.870
"Star Wars" had a much more
diverse cast, "The Foreigner"

00:14:34.870 --> 00:14:36.730
by Jackie Chan.

00:14:36.730 --> 00:14:39.640
Who's seen "The Foreigner,"
where the terrorists aren't

00:14:39.640 --> 00:14:40.750
dark-skinned people?

00:14:40.750 --> 00:14:42.410
That was brand new.

00:14:42.410 --> 00:14:44.530
And "The Big Sick," of course.

00:14:44.530 --> 00:14:46.900
And these are doing
really well financially.

00:14:46.900 --> 00:14:50.320
This is teaching machine
intelligence and the business

00:14:50.320 --> 00:14:53.720
world that this is a
pattern to take note of.

00:14:53.720 --> 00:14:56.000
I like Kumail Nanjiani's
quote, "there's so

00:14:56.000 --> 00:14:57.880
many movies from
different points of view

00:14:57.880 --> 00:14:59.520
that are making a ton of money.

00:14:59.520 --> 00:15:02.410
Don't do it because it's better
for society and representation,

00:15:02.410 --> 00:15:03.670
even though it is.

00:15:03.670 --> 00:15:05.830
Do it because you'll get rich.

00:15:05.830 --> 00:15:08.110
You'll get that
promotion, right?"

00:15:08.110 --> 00:15:10.540
This thinking
seems crass, yet it

00:15:10.540 --> 00:15:14.840
sits at the center of how
change will start to occur.

00:15:14.840 --> 00:15:18.190
And I believe that as we see
more of these kinds of things,

00:15:18.190 --> 00:15:19.630
wonderful things will happen.

00:15:19.630 --> 00:15:23.110
I want to close on my mother
went to see "Black Panther."

00:15:23.110 --> 00:15:24.220
This was her review.

00:15:24.220 --> 00:15:25.750
It went kind of viral.

00:15:25.750 --> 00:15:26.590
"Hi, John.

00:15:26.590 --> 00:15:28.540
Just came back from
seeing 'Black Panther.'

00:15:28.540 --> 00:15:31.150
It was very good."

00:15:31.150 --> 00:15:33.742
And we actually went to see
"Avengers" last, me and mom.

00:15:33.742 --> 00:15:34.450
I was in Seattle.

00:15:34.450 --> 00:15:36.310
And my mom is like 83 years old.

00:15:36.310 --> 00:15:39.040
She's like a little
woman with her cane.

00:15:39.040 --> 00:15:42.550
We're walking out of "Avengers"
and I said, mom, how was it?

00:15:42.550 --> 00:15:48.760
"Oh, it wasn't as good as
'Black Panther.'" So anyways,

00:15:48.760 --> 00:15:49.630
thank you.

00:15:49.630 --> 00:15:53.355
And we'll have Hannah next,
so please stay seated.

00:15:53.355 --> 00:15:55.295
